{
  "text": "Precipitation changes demonstrate substantial variation between and within the ensembles (figure 1b). In general, AO-PPE projects larger changes per 8C of DT g than CMIP3. Both ensemble means show positive annual mean precipitation anomalies in East Africa, and negative anomalies in some western regions, with greater than 80% model agreement in the direction of change. The dry signal is much more extensive and of a larger magnitude in AO-PPE, at greater than 90 mm yr rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org Phil Trans R Soc B 368: 20120298 negative anomalies occupy a larger proportion of the African tropics, including the south and west of the Congo Basin, where there is a negative anomaly greater than 16 mm month [CITATION_1] per 8C of DT g in the AO-PPE ensemble mean. This means there is inter-model agreement that dry seasons will intensify in regions where models agree that there will be no significant change averaged across the annual cycle (grey area in figure 1b) , or disagree in the direction of mean change (white area in figure 1b) . Therefore, even where there is considerable uncertainty about how the wet and dry season changes will average, there is consensus that precipitation will be reduced during dry seasons. The ensemble mean plots for both annual precipitation and MCWD 100 suggest a contrast in the precipitation signal between western and eastern equatorial regions. Areaaverages of 'west equatorial Africa' and 'central equatorial Africa' (figure 2) illustrate the spread of CMIP3 and AO-PPE model responses in each of these regions, and show how local changes develop as global temperature increases. Changes in AS-PPE associated with 2\u00c2 CO 2 are also shown. In central equatorial Africa, most models show little change or a modest wet signal. At 48C and beyond, none of the models shows negative anomalies. In west equatorial Africa, there is a great deal of spread between members of AS-PPE in the direction and magnitude of change, although more models exhibit a dry signal than a wet signal. In the transient ensembles, there is little significant change at 18C, but from 28C there is a progressive decrease in MCWD 100 and from 38C this is greater than 100 mm month 21 in some versions of HadCM3. Note that the boxplots in figure 2 are based on a different number of models at each DT g interval, but that individual models also show progressive change as global temperature rises. The projections of annual precipitation and MCWD 100 change presented here exhibit variation between models in terms of the direction, magnitude and spatial pattern of change; but there is one signal which emerges from many different models within the core rainforest zone: a drying in west equatorial Africa. There have been indications of such a signal in previous literature based on annual mean precipitation [CITATION_2] . When measured here as MCWD 100 , the pattern shows consistency between models and the dry signal extends over a larger proportion of the Congo Basin. In \u00a74, mechanisms associated with drying in this region are explored.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "4382228",
    "[CITATION_2]": "129417548"
